{"id":"1212.1808","submitter":"MirFaez Miri","authors":"Sahar Pakdel and MirFaez Miri","title":"Faraday Rotation and Circular Dichroism Spectra of Gold and Silver\n  Nanoparticle Aggregates","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.86.235445","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the magneto-optical response of noble metal nanoparticle clusters.\nWe consider the interaction between the light-induced dipoles of particles. In\nthe presence of a magnetic field, the simplest achiral cluster, a dimer,\nexhibits circular dichroism (CD). The CD of a dimer depends on the directions\nof the magnetic field and the light wave vector. The CD of a populous cluster\nweakly depends on the magnetic field. Upon scattering from the cluster, an\nincident linearly polarized light with polarization azimuth $\\varphi$, becomes\nelliptically polarized. The polarization azimuth rotation and ellipticity angle\nvariation are sinusoidal functions of $2 \\varphi$. The anisotropy and the\nchirality of the cluster control the amplitude and offset of these sinusoidal\nfunctions. The Faraday rotation and Faraday ellipticity are also sinusoidal\nfunctions of $2 \\varphi$. Near the surface plasmon frequency, Faraday rotation\nand Faraday ellipticity increase.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 8 Dec 2012 15:54:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-12"}
